==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Yokefellow
<hw>Yoke"fel`low</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Yoke</ets>
+ <ets>fellow</ets>.]</ety> <def>An associate or companion in, or as in;
a mate; a fellow; especially, a partner in marriage.</def> <rj><au>Phil.
iv. 3.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The two languages [English and French] became
<qex>yokefellows</qex> in a still more intimate manner.</q>
<rj><qau>Earle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those who have most distinguished themselves by railing at the
sex, very often choose one of the most worthless for a companion and
<qex>yokefellow</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Yokel</ent>⟦br⟧
